```
Subject,Description,Priority,Category
"Cannot login","I am unable to login to my account",1,Technical
"Billing error","I was charged twice for my subscription",2,Billing
"How to reset password","I need help resetting my password",3,General
"Server down","The API server is returning 500 errors",1,Technical
"Refund request","I would like a refund for last month",2,Billing
"Feature question","Does the product support SSO?",3,General
```

## Requirements

1. **Task type**: Multiclass text classification on structured tabular data → use **ML.NET** (NOT an LLM).
2. Tickets have: Subject (string), Description (string), Priority (int 1-3). Predict Category: Billing, Technical, General.
3. The existing 6-row CSV is too small for meaningful training. Expand `Data/tickets.csv` to ~30+ rows while keeping the original 6 rows intact as the first entries. Add realistic, diverse support ticket examples across all 3 categories.
4. Implement model training at app startup with evaluation metrics logged.
5. Expose a POST prediction endpoint.
6. Use `PredictionEnginePool` (thread-safe for ASP.NET Core) — never use a singleton PredictionEngine.

## Implementation plan

### 1. Expand Data/tickets.csv
Add ~25 more realistic rows covering all 3 categories with varied subjects/descriptions and priorities.

### 2. Add NuGet packages
Add to .csproj:
- `Microsoft.ML` Version="4.*"
- `Microsoft.Extensions.ML` Version="4.*" (provides PredictionEnginePool)

### 3. Create Models/TicketData.cs
```csharp
using Microsoft.ML.Data;

namespace TicketClassifier.Models;

public class TicketInput
{
    [LoadColumn(0)]
    public string Subject { get; set; } = string.Empty;

    [LoadColumn(1)]
    public string Description { get; set; } = string.Empty;

    [LoadColumn(2)]
    public float Priority { get; set; }

    [LoadColumn(3)]
    public string Category { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}

public class TicketPrediction
{
    [ColumnName("PredictedLabel")]
    public string PredictedCategory { get; set; } = string.Empty;

    public float[] Score { get; set; } = [];
}
```

Note: Priority must be `float` for ML.NET feature concatenation.

### 4. Create Services/TicketModelTrainer.cs
A service that:
- Loads data from CSV
- Builds a pipeline: FeaturizeText on Subject, FeaturizeText on Description, convert Priority to float, Concatenate all into "Features", MapValueToKey on Category → Label, use SdcaMaximumEntropy trainer, MapKeyToValue on PredictedLabel
- Splits data with TrainTestSplit (testFraction: 0.2)
- Trains on training set
- Evaluates on test set and logs metrics (MacroAccuracy, MicroAccuracy, LogLoss, per-class metrics)
- Saves model to a .zip file
- Returns path to saved model

Use `MLContext(seed: 42)` for reproducibility.

### 5. Create Controllers/TicketController.cs
```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.Extensions.ML;
using TicketClassifier.Models;

namespace TicketClassifier.Controllers;

[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class TicketController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly PredictionEnginePool<TicketInput, TicketPrediction> _predictionEnginePool;

    public TicketController(PredictionEnginePool<TicketInput, TicketPrediction> predictionEnginePool)
    {
        _predictionEnginePool = predictionEnginePool;
    }

    [HttpPost("classify")]
    public ActionResult<TicketClassificationResponse> Classify([FromBody] TicketClassificationRequest request)
    {
        var input = new TicketInput
        {
            Subject = request.Subject,
            Description = request.Description,
            Priority = request.Priority
        };

        var prediction = _predictionEnginePool.Predict(input);

        return Ok(new TicketClassificationResponse
        {
            PredictedCategory = prediction.PredictedCategory,
            Confidence = prediction.Score.Max()
        });
    }
}

public class TicketClassificationRequest
{
    public string Subject { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Description { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public int Priority { get; set; }
}

public class TicketClassificationResponse
{
    public string PredictedCategory { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public float Confidence { get; set; }
}
```

### 6. Update Program.cs
- Train the model at startup via the trainer service
- Register `PredictionEnginePool` using `.FromFile(modelPath)`
- Keep AddControllers and MapControllers

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.ML;
using TicketClassifier.Models;
using TicketClassifier.Services;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddControllers();

// Train model at startup
var trainer = new TicketModelTrainer(builder.Environment);
var (modelPath, metrics) = trainer.TrainAndEvaluate();

// Log metrics
Console.WriteLine("=== Model Evaluation Metrics ===");
Console.WriteLine($"Macro Accuracy: {metrics.MacroAccuracy:F4}");
Console.WriteLine($"Micro Accuracy: {metrics.MicroAccuracy:F4}");
Console.WriteLine($"Log Loss:       {metrics.LogLoss:F4}");
Console.WriteLine($"Log Loss Reduction: {metrics.LogLossReduction:F4}");
Console.WriteLine();
Console.WriteLine("Per-class metrics:");
Console.WriteLine(metrics.ConfusionMatrix.GetFormattedConfusionTable());
Console.WriteLine("================================");

// Register pooled prediction engine
builder.Services.AddPredictionEnginePool<TicketInput, TicketPrediction>()
    .FromFile(modelPath);

var app = builder.Build();
app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
```

### 7. Build and verify
Run `dotnet build` to verify no errors.

## Important guardrails (from technology-selection skill)
- Always set seed: `new MLContext(seed: 42)`
- Always use TrainTestSplit — never evaluate on training data
- Always use PredictionEnginePool in ASP.NET Core, never singleton PredictionEngine
- Log evaluation metrics
- Ensure the model .zip is saved under a known path

## Execution
1. Edit Data/tickets.csv to expand training data
2. Edit TicketClassifier.csproj to add packages
3. Run `dotnet restore`
4. Create directories: Models, Services, Controllers
5. Create all source files
6. Update Program.cs
7. Run `dotnet build` to verify
8. Fix any issues

Do all the work. Create the files. Build the project. Fix any compilation errors. The final project must build cleanly.

